## 6. Broadcasting Rules

> Broadcasting lets NumPy operate on arrays of **different shapes** without copying data.
> Understanding this removes 80% of shape errors in ML code.

### The 3 Rules

```
Rule 1: If arrays have different ndim, pad the smaller shape with 1s on the LEFT.
         (3,) → (1, 3)

Rule 2: Dimensions of size 1 are stretched to match the other array.
         (1, 3) + (4, 1) → (4, 3)

Rule 3: If sizes differ and neither is 1, NumPy raises a ValueError.
```

```python
# --- Rule 1 + 2 in action ---
a = np.array([[1, 2, 3],    # shape (2, 3)
              [4, 5, 6]])
b = np.array([10, 20, 30])  # shape    (3,)  → padded to (1, 3) → stretched to (2, 3)

print(a + b)
# [[11 22 33]
#  [14 25 36]]

# --- Column vector broadcast ---
col = np.array([[100],      # shape (2, 1) → stretched to (2, 3)
                [200]])
print(a + col)
# [[101 102 103]
#  [204 205 206]]

# --- Outer product via broadcasting ---
x = np.array([1, 2, 3])       # shape (3,)   → (1, 3)
y = np.array([10, 20, 30])    # shape (3,)   → (3, 1)
outer = x.reshape(1,-1) * y.reshape(-1,1)
print(outer)
# [[ 10  20  30]
#  [ 20  40  60]
#  [ 30  60  90]]
```

> 💡 **Most common broadcasting in ML:**
> - Adding bias vector to a batch: `(batch, features) + (features,)`
> - Normalising: `(X - mean) / std` where mean and std have shape `(features,)`
> - Distance matrix: `(N, 1, D) - (1, M, D)` → `(N, M, D)`

