## 7. Useful Aggregate Functions

```python
arr = np.array([[4, 7, 2, 9],
                [1, 8, 5, 3]])

# --- Global aggregates ---
np.sum(arr)         # 39
np.min(arr)         # 1
np.max(arr)         # 9
np.mean(arr)        # 4.875
np.std(arr)         # 2.59
np.var(arr)         # 6.73
np.median(arr)      # 4.5
np.cumsum(arr)      # running total (flattened)

# --- Along an axis ---
np.sum(arr, axis=0)   # [5 15  7 12]  — sum down each column
np.sum(arr, axis=1)   # [22 17]        — sum across each row
np.mean(arr, axis=0)  # [2.5 7.5 3.5 6.] — column means (feature means in ML)
np.max(arr, axis=1)   # [9 8]          — max per row

# --- Argmin / Argmax — returns INDEX of min/max ---
np.argmax(arr, axis=1)  # [3, 1]  — column index of max in each row
np.argmin(arr, axis=0)  # [1, 0, 0, 1] — row index of min in each column

# --- Sorting ---
np.sort(arr, axis=1)    # sort each row ascending
np.argsort(arr[0])      # [2, 0, 1, 3] — indices that would sort first row

# --- Where — conditional element selection ---
scores = np.array([0.82, 0.45, 0.91, 0.63, 0.88])
labels = np.where(scores > 0.75, "pass", "fail")
# ['pass' 'fail' 'pass' 'fail' 'pass']

# --- Unique values ---
classes = np.array([0, 1, 2, 1, 0, 2, 2, 1])
np.unique(classes)                  # [0 1 2]
np.unique(classes, return_counts=True)  # ([0,1,2], [2,3,3])  — class distribution
```

