## 8. Linear Algebra — `np.linalg`

> Linear algebra is the language of ML — weights, activations, covariance, and PCA are all matrix operations.

```python
# --- Dot product and matrix multiply ---
a = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])   # (2,2)
b = np.array([[5, 6], [7, 8]])   # (2,2)

dot  = np.dot(a, b)              # matrix multiply: [[19 22][43 50]]
matmul = a @ b                   # same as np.dot for 2D — preferred syntax
print(a @ b)

# Dot product of two vectors
u = np.array([1, 2, 3])
v = np.array([4, 5, 6])
print(np.dot(u, v))              # 32   (= 1×4 + 2×5 + 3×6)

# --- Matrix properties ---
A = np.array([[3., 1.],
              [1., 2.]])

det  = np.linalg.det(A)          # 5.0   — determinant
inv  = np.linalg.inv(A)          # inverse: A @ inv(A) = I
rank = np.linalg.matrix_rank(A)  # 2     — full rank
tr   = np.trace(A)               # 5.0   — sum of diagonal

# --- Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors (PCA core operation) ---
eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(A)
print("Eigenvalues :", eigenvalues)    # [3.73, 1.27]
print("Eigenvectors:\n", eigenvectors) # columns are eigenvectors

# --- Norms ---
x = np.array([3., 4.])
np.linalg.norm(x)          # 5.0     — L2 (Euclidean) norm
np.linalg.norm(x, ord=1)   # 7.0     — L1 norm (sum of abs values)
np.linalg.norm(x, ord=np.inf)  # 4.0 — max norm

# --- Solving a linear system  Ax = b ---
A = np.array([[2., 1.], [5., 7.]])
b = np.array([11., 13.])
x = np.linalg.solve(A, b)         # faster than np.dot(np.linalg.inv(A), b)
print(x)                           # [7.11, -3.22]

# --- SVD — used in dimensionality reduction ---
U, S, Vt = np.linalg.svd(A)
# A ≈ U @ np.diag(S) @ Vt
```

